  "pr_number": 20639,
  "issue_number": 11952,
  "issue_title": "type(var) is type(other) not considered enough",
  "issue_body": "**Bug Report**\r\n\r\nHi,\r\n\r\nFirst of all, thanks a lot for your work on mypy and the Python ecosystem in general!\r\n\r\nI am sorry if this has been reported before (I would imagine it probably has, but searching for things like \"type\" and \"is\" is, well, difficult). It seems that mypy does not realize that `type(a) is type(b)` is at least as strong a guarantee (well, actually, stronger) than `isinstance(a, type(b))`.\r\n\r\n**To Reproduce**\r\n\r\n(Write your steps here:)\r\n\r\n1. Run `mypy --strict` on the attached program (saving it with a .py extension beforehand).\r\n2. Watch it complain about the _bad functions returning Any instead of the declared type.\r\n3. Run the program to see that it, indeed, works.\r\n\r\n**Expected Behavior**\r\n\r\nNo diagnostic messages from mypy.\r\n\r\n**Actual Behavior**\r\n\r\nComplaints about functions that check that `type(result) is type(value)`.\r\n\r\n**Your Environment**\r\n\r\nChecked both with Python 3.9 + mypy 0.921 and Python 3.8 + mypy 0.910 on Debian testing. In both cases mypy was invoked with `--strict --python-version 3.8` and no additional configuration.\r\n\r\nThanks again, and keep up the great work!\r\n\r\nG'luck,\r\nPeter\r\n[mypytype.txt](https://github.com/python/mypy/files/7836286/mypytype.txt)\r\n",
  "merged_at": "2026-01-23T14:50:09Z",
